    "ai_explanation": "PROJECT OVERVIEW:\nThis is a modern frontend web application built using React for dynamic user interfaces and Vite for fast development and optimized bundling. It follows a component-based architecture, typical for single-page applications.\n\nEXECUTION FLOW:\nThe application starts from `JobSync-main\\src\\main.jsx`. This file is the primary entry point, responsible for rendering the root React component (`./App.jsx`) into the web page. It also imports global styles from `./index.css`.\n\nARCHITECTURE:\n- `/JobSync-main/public`: Stores static files that are served directly without processing (e.g., `index.html`, manifest, favicon).\n- `/JobSync-main/src`: Contains all the main source code for the application.\n- `/JobSync-main/src/assets`: Holds static assets like images, fonts, or icons used within the source code.\n- `/JobSync-main/src/components`: Houses reusable UI components that can be used across different parts of the application.\n- `/JobSync-main/src/components/Pages`: Contains the top-level components, each representing a distinct page or view of the application.\n\nTECH STACK:\n- **Frameworks:** React\n- **Build Tool/Bundler:** Vite\n\nNEW DEVELOPER GUIDE:\nTo understand the project, start by examining `JobSync-main\\src\\main.jsx` to see the application's initialization. Next, trace the import to `App.jsx`, which acts as the root component and typically orchestrates routing and main layout. Explore `src/components/Pages` to grasp the different views, and then `src/components` to understand the reusable UI building blocks. The core understanding order is: Entry Point (`main.jsx`) -> Root Component (`App.jsx`) -> Application Pages (`src/components/Pages`) -> Reusable UI Components (`src/components`).",
